MODE: ORCHESTRATOR
MUST_READ: AGENTS.md, ORCHESTRATOR.md
NOTE: Follow routing rules. Do not include acknowledgements in output.

You are an expert software architect and project planner.

Given the following project description, produce a task breakdown as a dependency DAG.

## Project Description

{project_description}

## Current Codebase Context

{codebase_context}

## Instructions

Analyze the project and produce a structured task list. Each task must have:
- A short unique ID (lowercase, hyphenated, e.g. "setup-backend", "auth-api")
- A clear title
- A role: domain | quality | ops
- Dependencies: comma-separated task IDs that must complete before this task (empty if none)
- A concise description of what the agent should implement
- Acceptance criteria (specific, testable conditions)

Optional per-task quality commands (use when the project is multi-stack or task-specific):
- LINT_CMD: shell command to lint this task's area
- TEST_CMD: shell command to test this task's area
- BUILD_CMD: shell command to build this task's area

If you include these, keep them short and runnable from the repo root.

Output ONLY in this exact format, one task per block, separated by blank lines:

TASK: <id>
TITLE: <title>
ROLE: <role>
DEPS: <comma-separated dependency IDs or "none">
DESCRIPTION: <what to implement>
ACCEPTANCE: <testable acceptance criteria>

[optional]
LINT_CMD: <lint command or "none">
TEST_CMD: <test command or "none">
BUILD_CMD: <build command or "none">

Rules:
- Order tasks so that independent ones come first
- Maximize parallelism: keep dependencies minimal
- Include at least one quality task (tests, linting)
- Include an ops task if CI/CD or deployment is relevant
- Keep tasks focused: each should be completable by a single agent
- Use realistic branch names derived from task IDs (e.g. agent-<task-id>)
